04552nam a22006735i 9789048516803DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20122013ne     fo  d z      eng d  a2012534003  a97890485168037 a10.1515/97890485168032doi  a(DE-B1597)502561  a(OCoLC)803370024  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL00aQC16.G635bL87 2012 4aQC7 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a301a9001 aLüthy, Christoph, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDavid Gorlæus (1591-1612) :bAn Enigmatic Figure in the History of Philosophy and Science /cChristoph Lüthy. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2012] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (225 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistory of Science and Scholarship in the Netherlands ;v1300tFrontmatter -- tTable Of Contents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Introducing Gorlæus -- tChapter 2. Gorlæus' Two Treatises -- tChapter 3. Gorlæus' Life -- tChapter 4. Gorlæus' Place In The History Of Seventeenth-Century Thought -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aWhen David Gorlæus, a prospective theology student, passed away tragically at twenty-one years old, he left behind two highly innovative manuscripts, which were published posthumously in 1620 and 1651, respectively. As his identity was unknown, seventeenth-century readers understood him both as an anti-Aristotelian thinker and a precursor of Descartes. In contrast, by the twentieth century, historians depicted him as an atomist, natural scientist, and even a chemist. David Gorlæus (1591-1612) seeks to pull together what is known of this enigmatic figure. Combining multiple historical sources, Christoph Lüthy provides a narrative of Gorlæus's life that casts light on his exceptional body of work and places it firmly at the intersection between philosophy, the nascent natural sciences, and theology. "Christoph Lüthy is the first to tell the complete story of David Gorlæus and to reconstruct his image on the basis of all remaining sources. Showing in a convincing way that Gorlæus is one of the key figures in the renewal of atomistic philosophy in the seventeenth century and a major influence on many philosophers that are much better known, he leaves us with the melancholy picture of someone who died too young to become one of the heroes of the scientific revolution."-Theo Verbeek, Utrecht University  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAtomism. 0aPhilosopherszNetherlands. 0aPhilosophyxHistory. 0aPhysicsxHistory. 0aReligion and science. 0aSciencexHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013z978311070067108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311060651508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z97831106627880 cprintz978908964438140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048516803?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048516803zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048516803/original  a978-3-11-060651-5 AUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066278-8 Amsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2002d2015  a978-3-11-070067-1 AUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA